<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41932784</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>03</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>03</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1557-9867</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>36</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Neuroimaging clinics of North America</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Neuroimaging Clin N Am</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Neuroimaging and the Epilepsy Journey.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>379</StartPage><EndPage>388</EndPage><MedlinePgn>379-388</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.nic.2025.12.001</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1052-5149(25)00865-2</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This article reviews the modern pathway of epilepsy care with a focus on how neuroimaging supports treatment decisions and guides surgical intervention for patients who are drug-resistant. The article details the roles of noninvasive and invasive diagnostic approaches including structural computed tomography and MR imaging, video-scalp electroencephalography (EEG) monitoring, PET, ictal/interictal single-photon emission computed tomography, magnetoencephalography, and invasive EEG monitoring, and it describes how these modalities are integrated to localize the epileptogenic zone and target surgical resection, laser ablation, or neuromodulation. A detailed case study illustrates the practical application of multimodal presurgical evaluation and stereoelectroencephalography-guided resection.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Brinkmann</LastName><ForeName>Benjamin H</For